data.content:
Your test works but uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)       → 
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)    → 
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)) — no built-in equivalent,
    // Assert.IsTrue is fine here, but add a message:
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // list.Single() + Assert.IsTrue(x != null) → 
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
    Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role);
}
```

**Key collection assertions available:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `Assert.Contains(x, list)` |
| `list.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |

The benefit: on failure, `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` tells you *"Expected count: 3, Actual count: 5"* instead of just *"Assert.IsTrue failed"*.
